## 11. Before/After Imagery (CSS filter approach — no real photos needed)

Use a single high-quality residential asphalt driveway photo from Unsplash (no attribution required):
- Recommended: https://unsplash.com/photos/cracked-asphalt-covers-the-entire-surface-MZgmNH6174Q (before)
- Or any wide, clean residential driveway Unsplash photo

**Before image:** `filter: grayscale(70%) brightness(1.35) contrast(1.1)` — makes it look faded/weathered
**After image:** `filter: brightness(0.88) saturate(1.25) contrast(1.05)` — rich, deep, freshly sealed

Use the `img-comparison-slider` web component (CDN: `https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/img-comparison-slider@8/dist/index.js`):
```html
<img-comparison-slider>
  <img slot="first" src="driveway.jpg" style="filter: grayscale(70%) brightness(1.35) contrast(1.1)" alt="Faded asphalt driveway before restoration">
  <img slot="second" src="driveway.jpg" style="filter: brightness(0.88) saturate(1.25) contrast(1.05)" alt="Restored dark asphalt driveway after treatment">
</img-comparison-slider>
```

